-- CELL: IMPORTER shadow · UNGROUNDED (numeric-literal) receiver.  Clauses S2 + S5, Fork 1.
--
-- ✅ REGRESSION FIXTURE for S1-RESIDUAL-B (closed 2026-07-14).  Every other importer fixture
-- (i1/i3/i4) uses a GROUNDED receiver -- a `Box`, a `Tok`, a `List` -- so the corpus was
-- structurally blind to this cell and graded 18/0 while it was broken:
--
--     import prov.{isEmpty}
--     main = println (isEmpty 0)     -- Type mismatch: Int literal vs Int Int
--
-- A numeric literal is `Num a => a`, so `inferShadowApp`'s `headTyconMono` said None, it
-- never reached its standalone arm, and it fell to the ordinary-app arm -- which types
-- against the METHOD scheme the env rebound the name to.  The prelude's
-- `Foldable.isEmpty : t a -> Bool` is HIGHER-KINDED, so unifying `t a` with the literal's
-- tyvar solved `t := Int, a := Int` -- hence the tell-tale `Int Int`.  The user's imported
-- `isEmpty : Int -> Bool` was never consulted.  PRE-EXISTING; not caused by the inversion.
--
-- Fix: give inferShadowApp the P0-20 groundShadowReceiver call its definer peer already had.
import prov.{isEmpty}

main =
  -- the IMPORTED standalone, on an UNGROUNDED literal receiver.  This is the regression.
  println (isEmpty 0)
  println (isEmpty 5)
  -- ⚠️ FORK-1 CONTROL, in the SAME fixture on purpose: an `import` is a SIBLING scope, not
  -- an inner one, so it does NOT shadow.  A receiver whose head HAS a live impl of the
  -- shadowed interface must still DISPATCH to the method.  If the inversion ever leaks onto
  -- importer shadows, these two lines reject or flip -- and the fix above cannot mask it,
  -- because grounding only chooses WHICH head the per-receiver rule is applied to.
  println (isEmpty [1, 2])
  println (isEmpty [])
